Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","Shangton, Leicestershire, England":"Shangton, Leicestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Wyleby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (West Midlands, especially Shropshire): variant of   Wiley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wiley","meanings":["English: from various places called with Old English <i>wīg</i>, <i>wēoh</i> ‘idol’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, clearing’, such as Whyly in East Hoathly (Sussex), Whiligh in Ticehurst (Sussex), Weeley (Essex), Weoley (Worcestershire), and Willey (Surrey), or from any of the other places called Willey, such as those in Cheshire, Herefordshire, Shropshire, and Warwickshire, named with Old English <i>wilig</i> ‘willow’ + <i>lēah</i>, or from Wylye (Wiltshire), which takes its name from the river Wylye (of uncertain etymology)."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice de Wyleby was born in 1325, in Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Robert de Wyleby, was 30 and her mother, Emma de Wyleby, was 27. She married Thomas Drakelowe in 1346. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1420, at the age of 95."},"et":{"1325–1420":"1325–1420","1320–1369":"1320–1369","1348–1378":"1348–1378","1350–1378":"1350–1378","1354–Female":"1354–Surnud","1295–1316":"1295–1316","1298–1388":"1298–1388","March 1378":"märts 1378","1350":"1350","1295":"1295","1316":"1316","1348":"1348","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1369":"1369","1346":"1346","1378":"1378","1388":"1388","1354":"1354","about 1369":"umbes 1369","1420":"1420","1298":"1298","1320":"1320","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wilby, Northamptonshire, England":"Wilby, Northamptonshire, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Shankton, Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shangton, Leicestershire, England":"Shangton, Leicestershire, England"},"fi":{"1325–1420":"1325–1420","1320–1369":"1320–1369","1348–1378":"1348–1378","1350–1378":"1350–1378","1354–Female":"1354–Kuollut","1295–1316":"1295–1316","1298–1388":"1298–1388","March 1378":"maaliskuu 1378","1350":"1350","1295":"1295","1316":"1316","1348":"1348","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1369":"1369","1346":"1346","1378":"1378","1388":"1388","1354":"1354","about 1369":"noin 1369","1420":"1420","1298":"1298","1320":"1320","Leicestershire, England":"Leicester